'''Tsukimoto Shrine''' (槻本神社) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in [[Takayama City]], [[Gifu Prefecture]]. It is identified as the {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft}} "Tsukimoto Shrine" in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|ja|延喜式神名帳|12=draft}} for [[Hida Province]]'s {{ill|Ōno District (Gifu)|ja|大野郡|12=draft}}.
The shrine's sacred cedar tree ({{ill|Cryptomeria|ja|スギ|12=draft}}) is designated as a Gifu Prefecture Natural Monument.<ref name="sugi">{{Cite web|language=ja|date= |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/tenki/takayamsi/tukimoto.html |title=Tsukimoto Shrine's Cedar Tree |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-20}}</ref> The tree is estimated to be over 1,200 years old, and local lore warns that those who harm it will quickly fall ill and die.
== History == The date of the shrine's founding is unknown. According to legend, the original sacred object was a giant {{ill|Zelkova|ja|ケヤキ|12=draft}} tree (槻), which continued to exist even after the construction of the shrine buildings. Another version of the legend attributes the sacred status to a giant cedar tree instead of a zelkova.
The current shrine structure was rebuilt in the 5th year of {{ill|Genbun era|ja|元文|12=draft}} (1740). In the 4th year of the [[Meiji era]] (1871), the shrine was designated as a {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft}}.
== Enshrined Deities == * [[Ōyama-tsumi|Ōyama-tsumi no Kami]] * [[Susanoo|Kushimikeno no Kami]] * [[Takeminakata|Takeminakata no Kami]] * [[Yasakatome no Kami]]
Alternate theories identify the deities as [[Ukemochi|Ukemochi no Kami]] and Tsukimoto Daimyōjin.
== Cultural Properties == * **Cedar Tree of Tsukimoto Shrine** - Designated as a Gifu Prefecture Natural Monument.<ref name="sugi" /> * **Monument Inscribed with the Shrine's name** - Designated as a Takayama City Historic Site.<ref>{{Cite web|language=ja|date= |url=http://www.city.takayama.lg.jp/bunkazai/bunkazai/siseki/index.htm |title=Historic Sites and Scenic Spots |publisher=Takayama City |accessdate=2013-04-23}}</ref>
== Access == * Approximately 7 km northeast of [[Takayama Station]] on the [[Takayama Main Line]]. ** Follow [[National Route 158]] eastward along the Yamaguchi Valley (a tributary of the [[Jinzū River|Miyagawa]]) from Nyūkawa Town, Yamaguchi. ** Alternatively, travel south from National Route 158 in Nyūkawa Town, Bōgata. Pass through the Nyūkawa Tunnel on the Hida Farm Road, then head west for about 1 km.
